TITLE: Mice/Roach Infestation
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: I am single mother of 2 little girls (4 and 5) when I took the tour of the property I specifically asked the leasing manager was there any infestation she said no nothing that has been reported. We moved in may 3, 2025. On may 4 I found a roach shell, may 5 started finding mouse droppings. And keep finding them.  I’ve made so many calls and maintenance request for an exterminator but they keep sweeping the problem under the rug saying they have to get approval from the owner. How expensive an exterminator is. They don’t care about the tenants only the money. They told me “if you’re having this problem other tenants should be too” but yet I’ve found dead roaches in the hallway. So tenants are having this problem they are just killing them, going on about their day and not making reports.

Once someone gets in the garage, which isn’t hard, they can go anywhere in the building. The doors to the stairs or the elevator do not lock. Some homeless man was just sleeping in his own throw up where the mailboxes were as I was taking my daughters to the dentist on Monday. Homeless people come in this building where tenants pay rent and sleep by the mailboxes or in the stairwell for free everyday. The property manager has yet to have people come fix or even look at the garage and doors that don’t lock since the shooting.

CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: My tenant Julio Ibarra has a dog onsite in the 2nd for apt. When I was there to collect rent, the dog lunged to attack me and my 9 yr old son. The dog was on leash but not under control by Julios 14 yr old son. The dog is vicious and needs to be reported as potentially dangerous. It's ok to have a dog that's protective but if you can't control it that's a public nuisance. I asked for the pets registration and pet liability insurance from the tenant. I haven't received it yet. When I asked the tenant on the 1St floor if she's had similar experiences with the dog, she said it went after her twins one day and she has to be careful when she leaves her apt with the children. A dog like this shouldn't be around children. If this happens again I want the dog off my property or removed by the proper authorities.

We recently had new windows put on the house which were very costly. My cats are only trying to protect their territory. The neighborhood does not want this “new cat colony” in the area, we lost most of the bunny and bird population last summer. We have seen no Robins at all this spring all due to the cats which have multiplied over winter. What can be done about this newly placed “colony”? TITLE: Light Nuisance
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
I am writing to file a light nuisance complaint concerning the flashing camera cart with a police-style light located in the parking lot of McDonald’s at 2520 W National Ave, Milwaukee, WI.

The flashing blue light from this camera cart shines directly past my closed blinds and into my apartment at night, located further down the road at 902 S 25th St. This constant and disruptive light has made it difficult to sleep and has become a significant nuisance.

I attempted to contact McDonald's directly to address the issue, but unfortunately, I did not receive any response. I also called their corporate toll-free number, but no one answered that call either. I am not sure whether McDonald's will take action on their own, so I am reaching out to your department in hopes that you can help resolve this situation.

I would like to request that the flashing blue light be turned off during the night or that the camera cart be moved to another part of the parking lot where the light does not affect nearby residents. This issue is causing unnecessary disturbance and discomfort, and I would appreciate any assistance you can provide in addressing it.

Thank you for your attention to this matter. I look forward to your response and any steps you may take to resolve this nuisance.

TITLE: Mice/Roach Infestation
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
I am writing to formally file a complaint regarding a recurring mice infestation in my rental unit at **902 S. 25th St., Unit #5**, Milwaukee, WI 53204. Over the past several weeks, I have noticed the presence of one or two mice on and off within the apartment, and despite my repeated concerns to my landlord, **Devoe Rentals LLC**, the issue has not been adequately addressed.

I have informed the landlord on several occasions about the mice problem, but their response has been dismissive and lacking in action. They have offered excuses and have not taken any concrete steps to resolve the issue. As a tenant, I am paying **$450 per month** for this rental, and I believe it is unacceptable for the landlord to ignore this serious health and safety concern.

I understand that **Devoe Rentals LLC** has a history of similar complaints with your department, and I am requesting that appropriate action be taken against this landlord for their failure to maintain the property in a habitable condition. The continued presence of pests in my apartment makes it difficult for me to live in the space comfortably, and I should not have to endure this while paying rent.

I am asking that you investigate this matter further and hold the landlord accountable for not addressing the issue. It is not fair to continue to pay rent in these conditions when they have not taken the necessary steps to address the problem.

Thank you for your attention to this matter. I look forward to hearing from you soon.

TITLE: Plumbing Problem
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
I am submitting a formal complaint regarding a persistent plumbing issue at **902 S 25th St, Milwaukee, WI 53204**, specifically with the second-floor bathroom tub.

The issue is that the bathtub in this bathroom fills with water whenever the shower head is in use, for no apparent reason. I am unsure whether this is an ongoing issue that has not been reported previously, or if it is a new problem that has gone unnoticed. Regardless, it is causing inconvenience and concerns regarding potential water damage or further plumbing complications.

I have informed my landlord, **Devoe Rentals LLC**, about this problem on several occasions, but they have refused to take any action or address the issue in any way. This lack of response has prompted me to reach out to your department for assistance.

Additionally, I have come to learn that Devoe Rentals LLC has a **history of complaints with the Milwaukee Department of Neighborhood Services**. It appears that they have a pattern of neglecting tenant concerns and providing substandard living conditions while continuing to collect rent payments from hard-working Milwaukee residents. It is disheartening to see that these landlords appear to operate without regard for the well-being or safety of their tenants.

Given the serious nature of the plumbing issue, the landlord’s failure to address it, and their history of neglect, I am requesting that the **Milwaukee Department of Neighborhood Services investigate this matter** as soon as possible. I would appreciate any assistance you can provide in ensuring that this issue is resolved in a timely and professional manner.

Thank you for your attention to this complaint. I look forward to your prompt response and resolution of this matter.

Nobody knows how to get in contact with the homeowner. They have not showed up in a year to move them, and they have continued to be a hazard to the public for a year. They also have overgrowth of weeds and vines that climbs our fence every summer, strangling our plants in our yard and causing our fence (3023) to lean. We sprayed our side with weed killer and now the debris is just laying dead in their driveway since last summer. I would assume that’s a fire hazard during burn advisories because it is dry, dead weeds. They also have jam packed gutters that cause water leakage into our basement and drown summer tomato plants in our gangways.

TITLE: Scattered Litter and Debris on Private Property
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
A man in the neighborhood, Kevin Tietz, residing at 4835 N 63rd St, Milwaukee, WI 53218, is a public health hazard. Not only is he a hoarder within the home and in his car, which has caused a plethora of insects and vermin to encroach within his property, but his mental illness has progressed, which is decreasing our property values. Kevin throws food on the side walk and within his front yard including: pork knuckle bones, ribs, turkey carcasses, rice, corn flakes, various fruits and vegetables, eggs, marshmellos, hot dog buns, bagles, and other products to name a few which are left overs he receives from the food pantry. This leftover waste ends up in my front and back yard or under my car, including the bones and scraps. This has also attracted unwanted rodents and other vermin to the area, including excess squirrels, raccoons, crows, mice, and furthermore attracted the stray cat population. The cats now take harbor under my deck and urinate consistently, ruining my yard. The problem is that much of the food which is laid out goes uneaten as these animals are not adapted to eat items, such as marshmallows and corn flakes. Several neighbors, including Edward Steward, residing at 6221 N 63rd St, Milwaukee, WI 53218, also have expressed to me that this debris has become a problem within his yard. We have expressed our dissatisfaction with the problem to Kevin in a pleasant manner, but he does not take our complaints seriously and continues the pattern. This has occurred for over 2 years and has only increased in the past few months. I am seeking help to stop this. I am concerned for my health as I recently found a rodent within my garage, which I know is attributable to this increase in left out waste. 
I was only able to attach one photo, but I have plenty more to shar

TITLE: Other Miscellaneous Forestry Request
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: The school does not pick up their leaves along the south and west sides of the property. I have lived down the road in this neighborhood for four years and every year the leaves pile-up along the sidewalk and alley. It is a nuisance for many reasons including that it makes the area look messy, it attracts garbage, people let their dogs poop all over it. I’ve also seen dead rodents buried in the leaves. I’d like my children to be able to play in the vicinity without being concerned about it. Also, In the winter, this area becomes a muddy mess and it’s so unnecessary if the school would just pick up these leaves year-round. I’ve attempted to contact the school directly but they do not have a public email that I could find.

TITLE: Interior of Building in Disrepair
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: I have been experiencing health issues since moving into this house in October. There is a storage room in the basement that has a very musty and mildew-like odor. You can’t see the source of the moisture, but you can smell it. In mid-December I first reported it to him. At first my landlord was very responsive and seemed to care. The first mold specialist that he sent looked at the room and said “oh, it’s a safe mold, if there is any mold” and did no testing whatsoever. Weeks later, I do my own mold testing and pay for it out of my own pocket. I followed the instructions exactly and tested in various areas in the room. Including by the pipe, by the walls (where the first mold specialist assumed there could be mold.) My testing showed Aspergillus, Penicillium, and Cladosporium was found. One of the samples I did right by the pipe and wall, and that was the most severe. I go to my landlord with all this information and share the reports and he sends a second mold specialist out to do his own testing. That was almost 3 weeks ago on January 13th and I haven’t heard one thing in response from my landlord about the results or any remediation plans. I think this is an uninhabitable condition for ME and MY family. I must be particularly sensitive to molds. A lot of people are so I’m not sure why everyone is downplaying this and not doing any further investigation. My dog is constantly itchy and can’t even stay at the house anymore. I am done being ignored by my landlord and I’m ready to figure out a solution or get me out of this house.

It's a great PR gesture for the city.   Urban planning journals talk about that strategy to mitigate urban CO2 generation.  Want Pictures?  Please forward to  Commissioner Kruschke.  He appears to be an innovative thinker and might like the idea.  Cost is pretty low - your seedlings are free.
